21:36.229 --> 21:38.896
and it's stronger
than I will ever be.

21:39.031 --> 21:42.600
You can resist but you
can't push it too far.

21:45.038 --> 21:48.972
CHRIS: Damn, it's
windy out today.

21:49.042 --> 21:52.643
Okay. You ready?
JESSI: I hope so.

21:52.712 --> 21:54.011
CHRIS: All right.

22:02.254 --> 22:03.987
Just trying to figure out
how to get a good whip,

22:04.057 --> 22:06.757
the rope is catching and like
slowing it down. JESSI: Yup.

22:10.930 --> 22:12.196
Success!

22:12.331 --> 22:15.666
Chris and I, we have
two large birch trees,

22:15.801 --> 22:18.602
and they have super
rotten cores,

22:18.671 --> 22:20.871
and we have to
take 'em down now.

22:20.940 --> 22:23.808
CHRIS: Yeah.
Tighten it up!

22:23.943 --> 22:25.343
JESSI: They're really
close to the house,

22:25.478 --> 22:28.813
these trees literally
can come down tonight.

22:28.948 --> 22:33.017
CHRIS: Nice. Start
putting pressure on it.

22:33.152 --> 22:36.954
Go until it's like,
zip line tight.

22:37.023 --> 22:41.091
There it goes.
Pulling good.

22:41.160 --> 22:45.496
It's starting to pull
away from the cabin.

22:45.565 --> 22:48.099
JESSI: It's getting
there; it's pretty stiff.

22:48.234 --> 22:49.734
CHRIS: Okay, I'm
gonna make some cuts.

22:56.976 --> 22:58.442
JESSI: Oh, wow.

23:02.048 --> 23:03.848
CHRIS: Starting to move.

23:04.583 --> 23:06.784
Whew! It's cracking!

23:10.056 --> 23:13.657
Just keep pulling until it gets
really tight, it's gonna pull over!

23:14.794 --> 23:18.996
There it is! Just bounce on that
cable and it will come right down.

23:19.131 --> 23:20.331
It's gonna go!

23:22.068 --> 23:24.735
I'm gonna cut it,
make sure it's tight!

23:33.212 --> 23:34.412
All right!

23:34.547 --> 23:37.681
JESSI: That's fantastic,
nothing got destroyed!

23:37.750 --> 23:40.617
CHRIS: Let's start prepping
for the next tree. JESSI: Yeah,

23:40.686 --> 23:42.186
it's gonna be a hard one.

23:44.757 --> 23:46.557
SONTA: You're always gonna
get taught a new lesson.

23:48.361 --> 23:50.361
When you're interacting
with animals,

23:52.899 --> 23:55.065
you're always gonna
get humbled by them.

23:58.905 --> 24:00.171
They're gonna put
you in your place.

24:00.306 --> 24:02.173
They're gonna teach you
something you didn't know before.

24:04.577 --> 24:07.111
Rubbing right up against here?

24:07.246 --> 24:08.846
CHEVIE: That steep
little bank right there?

24:08.981 --> 24:11.515
SONTA: Yeah. It looks like
there's kind of a little eddy in there,

24:11.584 --> 24:13.517
what do you think?
CHEVIE: Yeah.

24:16.255 --> 24:19.023
SONTA: This is an extremely
short window. CHEVIE: Hold on.

24:20.526 --> 24:23.861
SONTA: Oh. For us to be
able to get our spring whitefish.

24:23.930 --> 24:27.598
Because once they're
passed, it's out for the year.

24:28.667 --> 24:30.334
No going near the bank.

24:30.403 --> 24:33.337
You see how it falls so
easily into the river?

24:33.406 --> 24:36.791
CHEVIE: It's deep, too.
That's six to eight feet deep.

24:37.543 --> 24:39.810
SONTA: We'll see
what we see.

24:39.879 --> 24:44.081
Got a little blood on the
dip net, that's a good sign.

24:44.216 --> 24:45.416
SYDNEY: That's
'cause of the duck.

24:45.551 --> 24:47.618
(laughs)

24:47.753 --> 24:50.687
SONTA: The whitefish
are coming up,

24:50.756 --> 24:56.894
so we're facing in an eddy that
allows the fish to come into the net. Oh.

24:56.963 --> 24:57.895
CHEVIE: You felt
something already?

24:58.030 --> 25:00.430
SONTA: Felt
something already.

25:00.500 --> 25:02.833
So that's definitely
a good sign.

25:03.903 --> 25:06.370
CHEVIE: This is what it's all about is
getting on the water in the spring time,

25:06.505 --> 25:12.176
taking advantage of those things. Look
there's some nice animal tracks right there.

25:12.311 --> 25:16.847
That's probably a big black because
you don't see any nails in the sand.

25:16.916 --> 25:18.849
Brown have such long nails
you'll see those nails,

25:18.984 --> 25:21.385
they're very predominant.

25:21.454 --> 25:24.188
They're here looking for food
also so we start cooking fish,

25:24.323 --> 25:27.391
it increases the odds of seeing
one, but, uh, we gotta eat too,

25:27.460 --> 25:30.594
so we just gotta be on our
toes and keep the kids close.

25:30.729 --> 25:34.131
Just one of those, one
of those risks that we take.

25:34.266 --> 25:36.400
SONTA: Oh, that was
something. Let's hope.

25:41.891 --> 25:44.558
Y.
SYDNEY: Oh yay, we got one!

25:44.627 --> 25:46.960
SONTA: Wee! CHEVIE:
We're fishing now. SONTA: Yup.

25:47.029 --> 25:49.296
CHEVIE: I hope you flip it.
SONTA: Thanks.

25:49.365 --> 25:51.365
CHEVIE: How's that frame feel?
SONTA: Great.

25:53.435 --> 25:58.172
- That's a nice big fish.
- That's a big size. - Cool.

25:58.307 --> 25:59.607
SONTA: Pressure.

26:04.446 --> 26:07.815
Woo-hoo! Yes.
CHEVIE: Big fish. Big fish.

26:11.186 --> 26:13.454
SONTA: You know the goal
is really, to get, like,

26:13.589 --> 26:16.190
forty to fifty would be
awesome but if you get, ya know.

26:16.325 --> 26:17.591
CHEVIE: Holy.

26:17.660 --> 26:21.328
SONTA: Ten a day or more,
that's a good start for fishing.

26:23.065 --> 26:26.934
You know, every Innoko
River person is either out here

26:27.069 --> 26:31.705
or waiting for the fish in town. So,
everyone's kinda waiting on the white fish.

26:33.342 --> 26:36.143
One of the things that's really
important is just continuing with our

26:36.278 --> 26:44.278
cultural traditions, the activities that
make us who we are: Innoko River people.

26:44.753 --> 26:46.353
SYDNEY: This feels heavier.

26:46.422 --> 26:48.689
SONTA: This is
essential knowledge.

26:48.758 --> 26:50.758
You got something. SYDNEY: I
got something. I got something.

26:50.893 --> 26:53.694
SONTA: Wow. Something
that you pass on to your kids.

26:53.829 --> 26:56.463
Can you pull it all the way
over? SYDNEY: I think I can!

26:57.433 --> 27:00.634
SONTA: Wow, you picked
a good spot, Sydney.

27:00.703 --> 27:02.469
SYDNEY: Don't take
my spot, mother.

27:11.447 --> 27:14.781
KALEB: There's an animal
control specialist

27:14.850 --> 27:17.284
who takes care of problems
like this in the city.

27:18.187 --> 27:20.921
I don't have that option.

27:21.056 --> 27:23.590
I am the animal
control specialist.

27:24.927 --> 27:27.327
Oh yeah, look at that one.

27:27.396 --> 27:30.397
That's holding back some water.

27:30.532 --> 27:34.001
You have to take beaver dams the
exact same way they went together:

27:34.070 --> 27:36.269
one piece at a time.

27:36.339 --> 27:39.640
Try and do it more than
that, you will not succeed.

27:40.543 --> 27:43.043
Beavers are such
incredible engineers.

27:45.681 --> 27:50.550
You're looking like a foreman
and less like a worker there, Gilbert.

27:50.619 --> 27:54.488
Gilbert, he's not much help with
this dam removal, but that's okay.

27:54.557 --> 27:58.559
He's learning an
important lesson about

27:58.694 --> 28:01.628
taking care of the
resources that are given to us

28:01.764 --> 28:03.964
and being good
stewards of the land.

28:05.501 --> 28:11.571
This dam starts back behind that big
spruce tree and goes all the way here,

28:11.640 --> 28:17.244
all the way down a hundred feet that
way and then crosses another little ways.

28:17.313 --> 28:21.048
But we're trying to make this as
inhospitable as possible for beavers,

28:21.183 --> 28:23.283
so they don't
wanna stick around.

28:24.854 --> 28:26.587
Before we did all this work

28:26.722 --> 28:29.990
this would've been a pretty
sweet place for a beaver to move in.

28:30.059 --> 28:36.129
Unpack their bags, and, uh, enjoy a
nice summer without a whole lotta work,

28:36.198 --> 28:38.665
but we're trying to make
it so they have to build

28:38.801 --> 28:40.133
a lot of infrastructure
to move in here.

28:40.202 --> 28:42.736
GILBERT: They don't have
a bag.

28:42.805 --> 28:44.138
KALEB: It's metaphorical,
Gilbert.

28:49.945 --> 28:53.347
JHONNY: I grew up as a bum,
you know, bumming around.

28:53.482 --> 28:57.017
To just live a stagnate
life doesn't work for me.

28:58.287 --> 29:01.688
The closer I am to
excitement, danger, thrills,

29:01.774 --> 29:03.891
and death, the more
I feel alive.

29:11.166 --> 29:13.400
You ready, Java? Huh?

29:16.505 --> 29:17.738
Buckle in.

29:23.178 --> 29:25.979
I've seen bears on this shore.

29:26.048 --> 29:28.181
Stalked one last night.

29:28.250 --> 29:31.919
It ran up into the trees,
into the bushes. Got lost.

29:32.054 --> 29:35.722
Wasn't able to find it, but
I've seen activity in this area.

29:35.791 --> 29:41.195
I'm gonna kinda focus,
concentrate my time right in here.

30:12.361 --> 30:15.262
All right Java, I see a bear.

30:21.370 --> 30:23.237
It's a bear. I got a bear.

30:25.574 --> 30:28.308
You stay, Java. Stay.

30:38.387 --> 30:41.054
Ears on. You gonna
listen? Huh?

30:41.190 --> 30:46.059
You gonna behave? Really
easy, okay? Let's go.

30:49.731 --> 30:53.267
You gotta go around this
corner and put the stalk on.

30:57.873 --> 31:00.607
(bleep). Slippery.

31:13.488 --> 31:14.855
Oh, yeah, he's feeding.

31:16.291 --> 31:19.059
He's eating a bunch of
grass right now, feeding.

31:20.562 --> 31:21.795
It's kinda sat down.

31:24.099 --> 31:25.832
That thing is (bleep) big.
It's a big bear.

31:29.572 --> 31:30.904
Good girl. Good girl.

31:31.907 --> 31:34.308
Do you remember when I
rubbed this bullet on your face?

31:40.649 --> 31:42.082
That was a good look, wasn't it?

31:43.652 --> 31:46.053
Whoa, that's a big bear.

31:47.923 --> 31:49.623
(sighs)

31:53.929 --> 31:56.029
Easy, easy Java. Easy.

32:01.937 --> 32:05.672
When hunting predators,
especially when I have Java with me.

32:05.741 --> 32:08.408
Hey, hey, Java. Easy.

32:08.543 --> 32:12.479
It's important I take the bear
down with one clean shot.

32:27.563 --> 32:30.797
I gotta wait for it to turn
sideways so I can get a clean shot.

32:37.706 --> 32:37.938
(gunfire)

32:58.777 --> 32:59.743
JHONNY: I think I
got a down bear.

33:13.458 --> 33:14.157
Wow.

33:19.064 --> 33:20.397
Java, come here.

33:21.333 --> 33:23.066
That's a good
girl. Huh?

33:23.135 --> 33:25.668
That's a good girl.
You did so good.

33:25.738 --> 33:27.204
Yeah, I know you smell it.

33:27.339 --> 33:28.538
The wind's blowing
right toward us.

33:31.810 --> 33:38.548
He looks good as dead, but we'll
just have to go over there and find out.

33:38.683 --> 33:40.017
This isn't a caribou.

33:41.686 --> 33:42.753
Come on girl.

33:50.429 --> 33:53.663
Yeah, looking pretty
dead from here.

34:01.506 --> 34:04.775
Yeah. It's dead.

34:07.579 --> 34:10.814
Watch out, Java. Watch out.
Come on. Java, watch out.

34:15.054 --> 34:16.453
Hey, stay back.

34:17.189 --> 34:19.990
Look at those, those teeth.

34:20.125 --> 34:21.525
Something you don't
want coming at you.

34:27.800 --> 34:31.601
Bears and I are both
opportunistic hunters.

34:31.670 --> 34:35.372
We both like to wander. We
both like to be alone.

34:37.142 --> 34:39.609
I see a lot of myself in bears,

34:39.744 --> 34:43.013
but that doesn't exclude
me from being a hunter.

34:43.148 --> 34:48.085
The middle of nowhere in Alaska, next
to a bear that's gonna feed Java and I

34:48.220 --> 34:51.955
for spring into summer.

34:52.090 --> 34:55.692
Having a connection to the
food I eat is a big driving force

34:55.827 --> 34:59.229
to why I live this lifestyle,

34:59.364 --> 35:04.901
because every meal I make
now has a story to tell,

35:05.036 --> 35:06.970
and I remember
having this bullet

35:07.105 --> 35:09.439
and I put it on Java's nose.

35:09.508 --> 35:13.443
I kinda rubbed it a
little luck on, on Java,

35:13.578 --> 35:17.180
'cause this is her first
bear hunt, and uh,

35:17.249 --> 35:19.516
here I am holding that
bullet. That's really really cool.

35:24.590 --> 35:26.656
All right Java, you keep your eye
on this. We're gonna hang onto that.

35:26.791 --> 35:30.527
That's kinda a neat souvenir. I feel
like I got my money back with that one.

35:35.400 --> 35:36.566
Big old testicle.

35:40.806 --> 35:42.239
Puts me to shame.

35:47.145 --> 35:51.948
JESSI: I'm a knife out here, and
the Cosna is the sharpening stone,

35:52.083 --> 35:54.484
and I constantly
have to stay sharp,

35:57.222 --> 36:02.158
'cause as soon as I become dull you
know something's gonna come my way

36:02.227 --> 36:03.827
and I won't be able to cut it.

36:09.167 --> 36:11.368
CHRIS: All right, that's looking
pretty good, I'm gonna come down.

36:11.503 --> 36:15.105
JESSI: Okay. I
got the ladder.

36:15.240 --> 36:18.909
CHRIS: So now I'm gonna figure
out how to get this tree down.

36:19.044 --> 36:19.976
JESSI: Welcome
back to earth.

36:20.045 --> 36:22.512
CHRIS: Oh, it feels
good to be down.

36:22.581 --> 36:24.514
JESSI: All right, let's
take this outta here.

36:24.649 --> 36:27.250
CHRIS: This one worries
me so close to the house.

36:27.319 --> 36:28.585
Nice.

36:30.255 --> 36:33.023
Awesome. I'll
get the cable.

36:36.328 --> 36:39.329
JESSI: So, the cable is strung
up from the rotten birch tree.

36:39.464 --> 36:41.664
It's gonna over to
a healthier tree.

36:41.733 --> 36:45.068
CHRIS: Can't wait to get these
trees down and not worry anymore.

36:45.137 --> 36:47.470
JESSI: It's gonna go
down along a pulley.

36:47.606 --> 36:52.342
CHRIS: Okay. Everything
looks really good.

36:52.477 --> 36:57.147
JESSI: It's gonna go to second
pulley connected to another spruce tree.

36:57.282 --> 37:01.884
Okay, there it is. I
think that works, right?

37:01.954 --> 37:05.355
CHRIS: Yeah, it's gonna
come right across here.

37:05.490 --> 37:07.824
JESSI: So, this is
gonna be our weight.

37:07.893 --> 37:09.826
Keep the tension always.
CHRIS: Yeah.

37:09.895 --> 37:13.230
JESSI: Even when the
come-along doesn't pull anymore.

37:13.365 --> 37:14.564
CHRIS: Cool.

37:15.967 --> 37:17.634
JESSI: Chris and I are
gonna use a weight.

37:17.769 --> 37:21.838
When we took the first tree
down, I was acting as that weight,

37:21.973 --> 37:25.775
but in this small area
in front of our house,

37:25.844 --> 37:29.646
there's not a lot of places
to run from that tree.

37:29.781 --> 37:33.883
Every link in this whole
chain is important.

37:35.988 --> 37:37.120
CHRIS: Nice, it's
starting to float.

37:39.858 --> 37:42.025
JESSI: This is nice and tight.
CHRIS: Cool.

37:43.528 --> 37:46.496
JESSI: Nothing can loosen.
All right, here we go.

37:53.138 --> 37:54.371
CHRIS: Take it slow.

37:55.741 --> 37:57.474
All right, the
barrel's going up.

37:57.609 --> 37:59.442
JESSI: Tell me when you
see the tree moving.

38:03.015 --> 38:04.714
CHRIS: Dang, that barrel's
getting up there.

38:06.418 --> 38:09.352
Okay, it's starting
to crack up top.

38:09.421 --> 38:11.421
JESSI: Keep going?
CHRIS: Naw, that's it.

38:11.490 --> 38:12.689
She's ready to come down.

38:20.165 --> 38:21.331
Here it goes!

38:27.055 --> 38:29.055
JESSI: Oh, the barrel's
coming down. Watch out.

38:31.059 --> 38:32.192
(bleep)

38:33.729 --> 38:34.894
No.

38:40.935 --> 38:48.074
Whoa. CHRIS: (bleep)
yeah! All right! Woo! Yeah!

38:48.143 --> 38:50.076
JESSI: Good job.
CHRIS: Awesome.

38:50.145 --> 38:52.345
JESSI: Woo! That came
down like a big thud, right?

38:52.414 --> 38:54.881
CHRIS: I know, man,
my heart was slamming.

38:54.950 --> 38:55.815
JESSI: We still have
a lot of work to do,

38:55.884 --> 39:01.021
this thing is blocking
everything.

39:01.156 --> 39:03.356
KALEB: Piper, hey. Hold it,
hold it, hold it.

39:03.491 --> 39:07.627
GILBERT: Piper you tip
it over. KALEB: Good dog.

39:07.696 --> 39:10.497
Let's see if we can snake
our way out of these trees.

39:11.232 --> 39:13.199
We got in here somehow.
(laughs)

39:16.038 --> 39:19.039
The dam's torn out, and
we're back in the canoe.

39:19.975 --> 39:22.508
What a nice day on the lake.

39:22.577 --> 39:24.844
You enjoying learning
how to use the canoe?

39:24.979 --> 39:26.713
GILBERT: Yeah.

39:29.384 --> 39:33.186
KALEB: These moments that I
get to spend with Gilbert

39:33.321 --> 39:37.323
are something that can't
be replaced by anything,

39:37.392 --> 39:39.392
and I really hope
that this place sticks

39:39.527 --> 39:42.061
to his soul and he comes back,

39:42.130 --> 39:46.332
uses the resource and
continues this life.

39:46.468 --> 39:48.334
GILBERT: Dad?
KALEB: What?

39:48.403 --> 39:50.937
GILBERT: This is not
a beaver place at all.

39:51.072 --> 39:56.409
KALEB: Uh-huh. I cherish
my moments with Gilbert.

39:56.544 --> 40:00.346
It's time that
I'll never regret.

40:02.751 --> 40:06.686
CHEVIE: We caught somewhere
between fifteen and twenty fish.

40:06.821 --> 40:09.689
That's enough to keep Sonta busy
in the smokehouse for a little while

40:09.824 --> 40:11.491
and give some fish out.

40:11.626 --> 40:17.297
SONTA: Come. So, we have um my tavash and
the one that, who made this for you guys?

40:17.432 --> 40:19.632
RYDER: Grandpa! SONTA:
Grandpa, so hold on.

40:19.701 --> 40:24.904
These are really sharp. What you wanna
do is just hold right here on the gills.

40:24.973 --> 40:28.108
One of the things that's really
important is just showing the kids

40:28.243 --> 40:30.844
how to use these tools.

40:30.979 --> 40:33.646
Wash your hand right
here. To meet our needs.

40:33.715 --> 40:37.049
Here, put this whole thing
like this towards you.

40:37.119 --> 40:39.585
Cultural knowledge is
something that you don't change.

40:39.654 --> 40:41.721
I don't know everything. I
don't claim to know everything.

40:41.856 --> 40:46.259
But, you know, what I
am told, no, other way.

40:46.394 --> 40:47.460
Other way.

40:47.595 --> 40:50.830
I tell it the exact
same way to my kids.

40:50.932 --> 40:51.765
Okay, Emry, go ahead.

41:00.608 --> 41:06.746
JHONNY: I don't have
plans to have children,

41:06.848 --> 41:11.951
but I can see where people
do play a role in my life.

41:12.020 --> 41:14.621
So, right now I'm just
boiling this bear skull.

41:17.292 --> 41:20.093
You know I don't hunt for the
skull, I hunt for the meat,

41:20.228 --> 41:24.497
but to have that skull is just a
way to remember that hunt forever,

41:24.632 --> 41:26.966
keep that animal
alive in spirit.

41:27.101 --> 41:30.570
Okay, this is the hide here.

41:30.705 --> 41:32.972
Just gotta scrape
all the fat off.

41:33.041 --> 41:35.175
That's gonna help me
preserve this hide.

41:35.310 --> 41:38.911
It's not something
I'm gonna just waste.

41:38.980 --> 41:43.183
It was a really, really
successful hunt but it wasn't easy.

41:43.318 --> 41:45.718
And, uh, Java did
an outstanding job.

41:45.787 --> 41:48.655
She just sat right next
to me the whole time,

41:48.790 --> 41:52.124
and, uh, she's pretty tired from
the experience. You can tell,

41:52.194 --> 41:55.094
but we come back
here and we rest up.

41:56.398 --> 41:58.131
I just got a little
bit more work to do.

42:00.468 --> 42:04.270
CHRIS: It's just so much
work, but that's okay.

42:04.339 --> 42:10.276
JESSI: Oo-hoo. Chris,
check this out.

42:10.345 --> 42:12.745
CHRIS: Oh, what a mess.
JESSI: Right?

42:15.083 --> 42:16.616
CHRIS: When my dad
moved off the Cosna,

42:16.751 --> 42:19.886
he thought that nobody
would ever come back out here.

42:20.021 --> 42:22.622
But he kept coming back
and preserving the homestead

42:22.757 --> 42:25.358
